# BYOA agent setup

BYOA adds a user-authorized coding agent to an application. The developer owns the Cloudflare deployment. The end user connects their own supported agent account.

## inspect first

```bash
git clone https://github.com/rishabhsai/byoa.git
cd byoa
npm install
npm run check
```

Read `AGENTS.md`, `docs/architecture.md`, `docs/deploy.md`, `docs/demo.md`, and `docs/security.md` before changing the integration.

## deploy the runner

Requirements: Cloudflare Workers Paid, Containers, and an authenticated Wrangler session. R2 is required before enabling durable credential and workspace persistence.

```bash
npm run deploy
```

The deploy command creates `BYOA_APP_SECRET` when one is not provided. Save it in the developer backend, which exchanges it for short-lived browser session tokens. Never put it or a Cloudflare credential in browser code.

## add the client

Use `@byoa/sdk` for the protocol client. Use `@byoa/react` only if the app uses React. Packages are currently consumed from this repository and are not published to npm yet.

The example chat integration lives in `apps/demo` and is deployed at `https://byoa-demo.pages.dev`. Its connect flow remains explicitly offline until a production runner and its Pages secrets are configured.

## do not improvise around blockers

If Containers are unavailable, stop and enable them. The current alpha runner is ephemeral; do not imply durable sessions until R2 persistence lands. Do not replace tenant isolation with a shared process or store agent credentials in the workspace.
